1 Appendix S1 - Functions

This script includes the functions tetra, tri and di which compute chromatic coordinates in visual space for tetra-, tri- and di-chromatic visual systems respectively. These scripts need to be run before those detailed in Appendices S2-S5. Note that in order to run these functions you need to have the packages plyr and reshape2 installed.

It also contains the functions cov.Mtest and meanTest used to compare covariance matrices (Boxs M test by Michail Tsagris) and multivariate means respectively. Their use is described in Appendix S5.

1.1 Function tetra

function (Refl, Irr, Tetra, pcones = NULL, weber = NULL, doubleCone = NULL, wLong = 0.05, idVars = NULL, wlRefl = NULL, wlIrr = 1, irrIrr = 2, wlTetra = 1, conesTetra = 2:5, wlDoubleCone = 1, sensDoubleCone = 2, wlInclude = TRUE)

Arguments (similar arguments apply to functions tri and di)

Refl:
Reflectance data.frame in wide format: observations in rows and reflectances in columns, one for each focal wavelength; typically including also ID variables. Reflectance columns should begin with wl followed by the corresponding wavelength value in nm, e.g.: wl300, , wl700. Other columns are treated by default as ID variables. See idVars and wlRefl to change this behaviour.

Irr:
Irradiance data.frame. By default, tetra() assumes that wavelength values are stored in the first column, and irradiances in the second column. See irrWl and irrIrr to change default settings.

Tetra:
data.frame of cone sensitivities of a tetrachromatic eye. By default, tetra() assumes that wavelength values are stored in the first column, and that columns 2 to 5 store cone sensitivities to very short (VS), short (S), medium (M) and long (L) wavelengths respectively. See wlTetra and conesTetra to change default settings.

pcones:
vector of cone proportions of VS, S, M and L cones, expressed relative to the L cone.

Weber: vector of Weber fractions, overrides WLong and pcones.

doubleCone:
data.frame with double cones sensitivities. By default, tetra() assumes that wavelength values are stored in the first column, and sensitivities in the second column. See wlDoubleCone and sensDoubleCone to change default settings.

wLong Weber fraction of the L cone

idVars
names or indices of ID variables in Refl. When idVars=NULL, all variable names not starting with wl are considered ID variables.

wlRefl
names or indices of columns which store reflectance values in Refl. When wlRefl=NULL, column names starting with wl are taken as reflectance values.

wlIrr name or index of column which stores wavelengths values in Irr

irrIrr
name or index of column which stores irradiances values in Irr

wlTetra
name or index of column which stores wavelengths values in Tetra

conesTetra
names or indices of columns which store cones sensitivities in Tetra

wlDoubleCone
name or index of column which stores wavelengths values in DoubleCone

sensDoubleCone
name or index of column which stores cone sensitivities in DoubleCone

wlInclude logical, should Refl reflectances be included in the output?

#copy and paste into your R console to run these scripts first



tetra<-function (Refl, Irr, Tetra, pcones = NULL, weber = NULL, doubleCone = NULL, 

    wLong = 0.05, idVars = NULL, wlRefl = NULL, wlIrr = 1, irrIrr = 2, 

    wlTetra = 1, conesTetra = 2:5, wlDoubleCone = 1, sensDoubleCone = 2, 

    wlInclude = TRUE) 

{

    require(plyr)

    require(reshape2)

    IrrArg <- deparse(substitute(Irr))

    irrName <- names(Irr)[names(Irr) == names(Irr[irrIrr])]

    TetraArg <- deparse(substitute(Tetra))

    if (is.null(idVars)) {

        idVars <- names(Refl)[!(gsub("[[:digit:]]", "", names(Refl)) %in% 

            "wl")]

    }

    if (is.null(wlRefl)) {

        wlRefl <- names(Refl)[gsub("[[:digit:]]", "", names(Refl)) %in% 

            "wl"]

    }

    idRefl <- Refl[idVars]

    dfRefl <- Refl[wlRefl]

    ReflWl <- as.numeric(gsub("[[:punct:]]", "", gsub("[[:alpha:]]", 

        "", names(dfRefl))))

    names(Irr)[names(Irr) == names(Irr[wlIrr])] <- "wl"

    names(Irr)[names(Irr) == names(Irr[irrIrr])] <- "irr"

    names(Tetra)[names(Tetra) == names(Tetra[wlTetra])] <- "wl"

    names(Tetra)[conesTetra] <- c("VS", "S", "M", "L")

    commonWL <- Reduce(intersect, list(round(Irr$wl), round(Tetra$wl), 

        round(ReflWl)))

    if (!is.null(doubleCone)) {

        names(doubleCone)[names(doubleCone) == names(doubleCone[wlDoubleCone])] <- "wl"

        names(doubleCone)[names(doubleCone) == names(doubleCone[sensDoubleCone])] <- "sens"

        commonWL <- intersect(commonWL, round(doubleCone$wl))

        doubleCone <- doubleCone[round(doubleCone$wl) %in% commonWL, 

            ]

    }

    Irr <- Irr[round(Irr$wl) %in% commonWL, ]

    Tetra <- Tetra[round(Tetra$wl) %in% commonWL, ]

    dfRefl <- dfRefl[, round(ReflWl) %in% commonWL]

    reso <- unique(diff(Irr$wl))

    matrixRefl <- as.matrix(dfRefl)

    if (!is.null(doubleCone)) {

        irrDC <- cbind(doubleCone$sens) * Irr$irr

        dcCatch <- c((matrixRefl %*% irrDC) * reso)

    }

    irrcones <- as.matrix(Tetra[, c("VS", "S", "M", "L")] * Irr$irr)

    Tcatch <- (matrixRefl %*% irrcones) * reso

    if (!is.null(pcones) | !is.null(weber)) {

        if (!is.null(pcones)) {

            W <- (wLong/sqrt(pcones))^2

        }

        if (!is.null(weber)) {

            W <- weber

        }

        H <- c(1/sqrt(W[1] + W[2]), sqrt((W[1] + W[2])/(W[1] * 

            W[2] + W[1] * W[3] + W[2] * W[3])), sqrt((W[1] * 

            W[2] + W[1] * W[3] + W[2] * W[3])/(W[1] * W[2] * 

            W[3] + W[1] * W[2] * W[4] + W[1] * W[3] * W[4] + 

            W[2] * W[3] * W[4])))

        h <- c(W[2]/(W[1] + W[2]), W[1]/(W[1] + W[2]), W[2] * 

            W[3]/(W[1] * W[2] + W[2] * W[3] + W[1] * W[3]), W[1] * 

            W[3]/(W[1] * W[2] + W[2] * W[3] + W[1] * W[3]), W[1] * 

            W[2]/(W[1] * W[2] + W[2] * W[3] + W[1] * W[3]))

        TcatchTot <- apply(Tcatch, 1, sum)

        lcr <- log(Tcatch/matrix(rep(TcatchTot, 4), ncol = 4))

        x <- H[1] * (lcr[, 1] - lcr[, 2])

        y <- H[2] * (lcr[, 3] - (h[1] * lcr[, 1] + h[2] * lcr[, 

            2]))

        z <- H[3] * (lcr[, 4] - (h[3] * lcr[, 1] + h[4] * lcr[, 

            2] + h[5] * lcr[, 3]))

    }

    out <- data.frame(idRefl, wlResol = reso, Irr = paste(IrrArg, 

        irrName, sep = "$"), Tetra = TetraArg)

    if (!is.null(pcones)) {

        out <- data.frame(out, conesProp = paste(round(pcones, 

            2), collapse = ","))

    }

    if (!is.null(pcones) | !is.null(weber)) {

        out <- data.frame(out, WeberFrac = paste(round(sqrt(W), 4), 

            collapse = ","))

    }

    out <- data.frame(out, Tcatch)

    if (!is.null(doubleCone)) {

        out <- data.frame(out, DC = dcCatch)

    }

    if (!is.null(pcones) | !is.null(weber)) {

        out <- data.frame(out, x = x, y = y, z = z)

    }

    if (wlInclude) {

        out <- cbind(out, dfRefl)

    }

    out

}

tri<-function (Refl, Irr, Tri, pcones = NULL, weber = NULL, wLong = 0.05, 

    idVars = NULL, wlRefl = NULL, wlIrr = 1, irrIrr = 2, wlTri = 1, 

    conesTri = 2:4, wlInclude = TRUE) 

{

    require(plyr)

    require(reshape2)

    IrrArg <- deparse(substitute(Irr))

    irrName <- names(Irr)[names(Irr) == names(Irr[irrIrr])]

    TriArg <- deparse(substitute(Tri))

    if (is.null(idVars)) {

        idVars <- names(Refl)[!(gsub("[[:digit:]]", "", names(Refl)) %in% 

            "wl")]

    }

    if (is.null(wlRefl)) {

        wlRefl <- names(Refl)[gsub("[[:digit:]]", "", names(Refl)) %in% 

            "wl"]

    }

    idRefl <- Refl[idVars]

    dfRefl <- Refl[wlRefl]

    ReflWl <- as.numeric(gsub("[[:punct:]]", "", gsub("[[:alpha:]]", 

        "", names(dfRefl))))

    names(Irr)[names(Irr) == names(Irr[wlIrr])] <- "wl"

    names(Irr)[names(Irr) == names(Irr[irrIrr])] <- "irr"

    names(Tri)[names(Tri) == names(Tri[wlTri])] <- "wl"

    names(Tri)[conesTri] <- c("S", "M", "L")

    commonWL <- Reduce(intersect, list(round(Irr$wl), round(Tri$wl), 

        round(ReflWl)))

    Irr <- Irr[round(Irr$wl) %in% commonWL, ]

    Tri <- Tri[round(Tri$wl) %in% commonWL, ]

    dfRefl <- dfRefl[, round(ReflWl) %in% commonWL]

    reso <- unique(diff(Irr$wl))

    matrixRefl <- as.matrix(dfRefl)

    irrcones <- as.matrix(Tri[, c("S", "M", "L")] * Irr$irr)

    Tcatch <- (matrixRefl %*% irrcones) * reso

    if (!is.null(pcones) | !is.null(weber)) {

        if (!is.null(pcones)) {

            W <- (wLong/sqrt(pcones))^2

        }

        if (!is.null(weber)) {

            W <- weber

        }

        H <- c(1/sqrt(W[1] + W[2]), sqrt((W[1] + W[2])/(W[1] * 

            W[2] + W[1] * W[3] + W[2] * W[3])))

        h <- c(W[2]/(W[1] + W[2]), W[1]/(W[1] + W[2]))

        TcatchTot <- apply(Tcatch, 1, sum)

        lcr <- log(Tcatch/matrix(rep(TcatchTot, 3), ncol = 3))

        x <- H[1] * (lcr[, 1] - lcr[, 2])

        y <- H[2] * (lcr[, 3] - (h[1] * lcr[, 1] + h[2] * lcr[, 

            2]))

    }

    out <- data.frame(idRefl, wlResol = reso, Irr = paste(IrrArg, 

        irrName, sep = "$"), Tri = TriArg)

    if (!is.null(pcones)) {

        out <- data.frame(out, conesProp = paste(round(pcones, 

            2), collapse = ","))

    }

    if (!is.null(pcones) | !is.null(weber)) {

        out <- data.frame(out, WeberFrac = paste(round(sqrt(W), 4), 

            collapse = ","))

    }

    out <- data.frame(out, Tcatch)

    if (!is.null(pcones) | !is.null(weber)) {

        out <- data.frame(out, x = x, y = y)

    }

    if (wlInclude) {

        out <- cbind(out, dfRefl)

    }

    out

}

di<-function (Refl, Irr, Bi, pcones = NULL, weber = NULL, wLong = 0.05, 

    idVars = NULL, wlRefl = NULL, wlIrr = 1, irrIrr = 2, wlBi = 1, 

    conesBi = 2:3, wlInclude = TRUE) 

{

    require(plyr)

    require(reshape2)

    IrrArg <- deparse(substitute(Irr))

    irrName <- names(Irr)[names(Irr) == names(Irr[irrIrr])]

    BiArg <- deparse(substitute(Bi))

    if (is.null(idVars)) {

        idVars <- names(Refl)[!(gsub("[[:digit:]]", "", names(Refl)) %in% 

            "wl")]

    }

    if (is.null(wlRefl)) {

        wlRefl <- names(Refl)[gsub("[[:digit:]]", "", names(Refl)) %in% 

            "wl"]

    }

    idRefl <- Refl[idVars]

    dfRefl <- Refl[wlRefl]

    ReflWl <- as.numeric(gsub("[[:punct:]]", "", gsub("[[:alpha:]]", 

        "", names(dfRefl))))

    names(Irr)[names(Irr) == names(Irr[wlIrr])] <- "wl"

    names(Irr)[names(Irr) == names(Irr[irrIrr])] <- "irr"

    names(Bi)[names(Bi) == names(Bi[wlBi])] <- "wl"

    names(Bi)[conesBi] <- c("S", "L")

    commonWL <- Reduce(intersect, list(round(Irr$wl), round(Bi$wl), 

        round(ReflWl)))

    Irr <- Irr[round(Irr$wl) %in% commonWL, ]

    Bi <- Bi[round(Bi$wl) %in% commonWL, ]

    dfRefl <- dfRefl[, round(ReflWl) %in% commonWL]

    reso <- unique(diff(Irr$wl))

    matrixRefl <- as.matrix(dfRefl)

    irrcones <- as.matrix(Bi[, c("S", "L")] * Irr$irr)

    Tcatch <- (matrixRefl %*% irrcones) * reso

    if (!is.null(pcones) | !is.null(weber)) {

        if (!is.null(pcones)) {

            W <- (wLong/sqrt(pcones))^2

        }

        if (!is.null(weber)) {

            W <- weber

        }

        H <- c(1/sqrt(W[1] + W[2]))

        TcatchTot <- apply(Tcatch, 1, sum)

        lcr <- log(Tcatch/matrix(rep(TcatchTot, 2), ncol = 2))

        x <- H[1] * (lcr[, 1] - lcr[, 2])

    }

    out <- data.frame(idRefl, wlResol = reso, Irr = paste(IrrArg, 

        irrName, sep = "$"), Bi = BiArg)

    if (!is.null(pcones)) {

        out <- data.frame(out, conesProp = paste(round(pcones, 

            2), collapse = ","))

    }

    if (!is.null(pcones) | !is.null(weber)) {

        out <- data.frame(out, WeberFrac = paste(round(sqrt(W), 4), 

            collapse = ","))

    }

    out <- data.frame(out, Tcatch)

    if (!is.null(pcones) | !is.null(weber)) {

        out <- data.frame(out, x = x)

    }

    if (wlInclude) {

        out <- cbind(out, dfRefl)

    }

    out

}

1.4 Function cov.Mtest by Michail Tsagris

#BOx's M test for the equality of covariance matrices

#by Michail Tsagris from http://www.academia.edu/1887808/Multivariate_statistical_functions_in_R



cov.Mtest=function(x,ina,a=0.05) {

  ## x is the data set

  ## ina is a numeric vector indicating the groups of the data set

  ## a is the significance level, set to 0.05 by default

  x=as.matrix(x)

  p=ncol(x)   ## dimension of the data 

  n=nrow(x)   ## total sample size

  k=max(ina)   ## number of groups

  nu=rep(0,k)   ## the sample size of each group will be stored here later

  pame=rep(0,k)   ## the determinant of each covariance will be stored here

  ## the next "for" function calculates the covariance matrix of each group

  

  nu=as.vector(table(ina)) 

  mat=mat1=array(dim=c(p,p,k))

  for (i in 1:k) { 

    mat[,,i]=cov(x[ina==i,])

    pame[i]=det(mat[,,i]) ## the detemirnant of each covariance matrix 

    mat1[,,i]=(nu[i]-1)*cov(x[ina==i,]) }

  ## the next 2 lines calculate the pooled covariance matrix

  Sp=apply(mat1,1:2,sum)

  Sp=Sp/(n-k)

  for (i in 1:k)

    pamela=det(Sp) ## determinant of the pooled covariance matrix

  test1=sum((nu-1)*log(pamela/pame))

  gama1=(2*(p^2)+3*p-1)/(6*(p+1)*(k-1))

  gama2=(sum(1/(nu-1))-1/(n-k))

  gama=1-gama1*gama2

  test=gama*test1 ## this is the M (test statistic)

  df=0.5*p*(p+1)*(k-1) ## degrees of freedom of the chi-square distribution

  pvalue=1-pchisq(test,df) ## p-value of the test statistic

  crit=qchisq(1-a,df) ## critical value of the chi-square distribution

  list(M.test=test,degrees=df,critical=crit,p.value=pvalue) }

1.5 Function meanTest

x1 & x2 data frames with variables in different columns

test Type of test carried out: hotelling, approx or chisq. For more information see Appendix 3

meanTest <- function(x1, x2, alpha=0.05, test="hotelling"){

  p <- ncol(x1)

  n1 <- nrow(x1)

  n2 <- nrow(x2)

  x1bar <- apply(x1, 2, mean)

  x2bar <- apply(x2, 2, mean)

  s1 <- cov(x1)

  s2 <- cov(x2)

  delta <- x1bar-x2bar

  SCI <- matrix(rep(0, p*5), nrow = p)

  for(i in 1:p){

    SCI[i, 1] <- x1bar[i]

    SCI[i, 2] <- x2bar[i]

    SCI[i, 3] <- delta[i]

  }

  if(test=="hotelling"){

    s.pool <- (n1-1)/(n1+n2-2)*s1 + (n2-1)/(n1+n2-2)*s2

    T2 <- c(rbind(delta) %*% solve((1/n1+1/n2)*s.pool) %*% 

              cbind(delta))

    Fstat <- (n1+n2-p-1) * T2 / (n1+n2-2)

    c2 <- (n1+n2-2)*p/(n1+n2-p-1) * 

      qf(1-alpha, p, n1+n2-p-1)

    df <- c(num=p, den=n1+n2-p-1)

    p_value <- 1-pf(Fstat, p, n1+n2-p-1)

    for (i in 1:p) {

      SCI[i, 4] <- delta[i] - 

        sqrt(c2)*sqrt( (1/n1+1/n2)*s.pool[i,i] )

      SCI[i, 5] <- delta[i] + 

        sqrt(c2)*sqrt( (1/n1+1/n2)*s.pool[i,i] )

    }

  }

  if(test=="approx"){

    s.comb <- 1/n1 * s1 + 1/n2 * s2

    T2 <- c(rbind(delta) %*% solve(s.comb) %*% cbind(delta))

    aux1 <- (1/n1*s1 %*% solve(s.comb))

    aux2 <- (1/n2*s2 %*% solve(s.comb))

    aux1b <- 1/n1 * (sum(diag(aux1 %*% aux1)) + sum(diag(aux1))^2)

    aux2b <- 1/n2 * (sum(diag(aux2 %*% aux2)) + sum(diag(aux2))^2)

    nu <- (p + p^2) / (aux1b + aux2b)

    c2 <- (nu*p)/(nu-p+1)*qf(1-alpha, p, nu-p+1)

    Fstat <- (nu-p+1)*T2/(nu*p)

    df <- c(num=p, den=nu-p+1)

    p_value <- 1-pf(Fstat, p, nu-p+1)

    for (i in 1:p) {

      SCI[i, 4] <- delta[i] - 

        sqrt(c2)*sqrt(s.comb[i,i])

      SCI[i, 5] <- delta[i] + 

        sqrt(c2)*sqrt(s.comb[i,i])

    }

  }

  if(test=="chisq"){

    s.comb <- 1/n1 * s1 + 1/n2 * s2

    T2 <- c(rbind(delta) %*% solve(s.comb) %*% cbind(delta))

    c2 <- qchisq(1-alpha, p)

    df <- p

    p_value <- 1-pchisq(T2, p)

    for (i in 1:p) {

      SCI[i, 4] <- delta[i] - 

        sqrt(c2)*sqrt(s.comb[i,i])

      SCI[i, 5] <- delta[i] + 

        sqrt(c2)*sqrt(s.comb[i,i])

    }

  }

  SCI <- data.frame(SCI)

  names(SCI) <- c("MeanSet1","MeanSet2","Diff","Lower","Upper")

  rownames(SCI) <- colnames(x1)

  list(test=test, alpha=alpha, df=df, 

       critical_value=c2, T2_stat=T2, 

       p_value=p_value,

       simultaneous_CI=SCI)

}

2 Appendix S2 - Introducing the functions and methods

You need to set the working directory to the folder where the data from the Supplementary material is stored using the function setwd().

Here we introduce the function tetra which computes xyz coordinates in perceptual space implementing the formulas from Cassey et al. (2008), which are based on the Vorobyev-Osorio model (Vorbyev & Osorio 1998, Vorobyev et al. 1998). Before running the scripts below you will have to run the formulas included in Appendix 1. Also make sure that you install packages plyr, reshape2, rgl and pavo.

The variable id indicates bird identity (ring number) while obs refers in this case to the part of the body that was measured. Notice reflectance spectra in rows and that each wavelength is preceded with wl.

Next, we can run the function tetra to compute cone quantum catches and coordinates in visual space.

Visual models require the following parameters: irradiance spectrum, cone sensitivity functions for the four single cones used for colour vision in birds and the relative abundance of each of these cones in the retina. For these analyses we used the spectrum of standard daylight (d65) as irradiance, which corresponds to open habitats (Vorobyev et al. 1998).

To set the irradiance spectrum in the function tetra (or tri or di, see below), one has to specify the data frame where the irradiance spectra are stored (Irr=Irr5nm) and which column to choose from (irrIrr=2; note that the first column is taken by the wavelengths here).

We used cone sensitivity functions of blue tits (Bennett et al. 2000) computed with the package pavo (Maia et al. 2013) which implements formulas from Govardovskii et al. (2000). For details on these computations see the documentation of pavo.

Cone sensitivity functions:

#sensitvity functions for the double cone used for achromatic tasks

bt.double.cone<-sensmodel(c(565), beta=T, oiltype = c("P"),lambdacut=417,  om= TRUE)



plot(bt.double.cone, ylab="sensitivity", main="blue tit double cone")

Single cones are used for colour vision in birds while double cones are thought to mediate achromatic discrimination. Here we focus on chromatic aspects but provide a brief instructions to quantify achromatic variability below.

We used cone proportions for blue tits (VS:0.374, S:0.709, M:1, L:1;obtained from Hart 2001). Using these cone proportions assumes that the L cone has a Weber fraction of 0.05 (note this can be changed with argument WLong=).This means that, following equation 10 in Vorobyev et al. (1998) the Weber fractions for the other cones are: VS:0.081, S:0.059 and M:0.05. If required Weber fractions can be entered directly with the argument WeberFrac=.

2.7 Linking PC1 to variation in spectra shape

Crown:

#assigns the dataset to be used

Data<-bt.crown

#computes quantiles on PC1 and PC2

Data$PC1q <-factor(1+(Data$PC1>quantile(Data$PC1, probs=0.25) & Data$PC1<=quantile(Data$PC1, probs=0.5))+2*(Data$PC1>quantile(Data$PC1, probs=0.5) & Data$PC1<=quantile(Data$PC1, probs=0.75))+3*(Data$PC1>quantile(Data$PC1, probs=0.75) & Data$PC1<=max(Data$PC1)))

Data$PC2q <-factor(1+(Data$PC2>quantile(Data$PC2, probs=0.25) & Data$PC2<=quantile(Data$PC2, probs=0.5))+2*(Data$PC2>quantile(Data$PC2, probs=0.5) & Data$PC2<=quantile(Data$PC2, probs=0.75))+3*(Data$PC2>quantile(Data$PC2, probs=0.75) & Data$PC2<=max(Data$PC2)))



bt.crown$PC1q<-Data$PC1q



#average spectra of the 4 quantiles belonging to PC1

spectra<-(aggregate(bt.crown[,16:96], by=list(q=Data$PC1q), mean)[,-1])



spectra<-na.omit(as.data.frame(t(spectra)))



wavelength<-seq(300,700,along=spectra$V1)





#finds the max reflectance to adjust ylim automatically 

ymax<-max(I(spectra$V1/mean(spectra$V1)), I(spectra$V2/mean(spectra$V2)), I(spectra$V3/mean(spectra$V3)), I(spectra$V4/mean(spectra$V4)))



#colours palette

col.pal<-topo.colors(n=5)



plot(I(spectra$V1/mean(spectra$V1))~wavelength, ylim=c(0, ymax), xlab="wavelength", ylab="normalised reflectance", pch=0, col="white")  

par(fig=c(0,1,0,1), new=TRUE)

lines(loess(I(spectra$V1/mean(spectra$V1))~wavelength, span=1), ylim=c(0, ymax), xlab="wavelength", ylab="normalised reflectance", lwd=4, col=col.pal[4])  

par(fig=c(0,1,0,1), new=TRUE)

lines(loess(I(spectra$V2/mean(spectra$V2))~wavelength, span=0.99), ylim=c(0, ymax), ylab="normalised reflectance", lwd=4, col=col.pal[3])

par(fig=c(0,1,0,1), new=TRUE)

lines(loess(I(spectra$V3/mean(spectra$V3))~wavelength, span=0.99), ylim=c(0, ymax), ylab="reflectance", lwd=4, col=col.pal[2])

par(fig=c(0,1,0,1), new=TRUE)

lines(loess(I(spectra$V4/mean(spectra$V4))~wavelength, span=0.99), ylim=c(0, ymax), ylab="reflectance", lwd=4, col=col.pal[1])

legend("topright", inset=0.05, title="quantiles", c("<25%", "25-50%", "50-75%", ">75%"), lwd=c(4, 4, 4, 4), col=c(col.pal))

2.8 Achromatic variability

Sensitivity to achromatic cues is apparently mediated by double cones by which have the same pigment as L cones in birds but have a yellowish-green oil droplet instead of the the red one found in L cones and thus have a wider sensitivity range.Double cone quantum catches are computed by function tetra and can be used to compute achromatic contrast.

This is usually done following Siddiqi et al.(2004) assuming the same Weber fraction as the L cone due to the fact that they have the same pigment. Values of achromatic contrast are thus measured in JNDs as well. By computing achromatic contrast between each reflectance spectrum and a reference spectrum we can obtain a scale of achromatic brightness measured in JNDs. As a reference we use a very low value of double cone quantum catch (close to zero, e.g.0.001) which would correspond to a very dark spectrum. Higher values thus correspond to spectra with higher absolute reflectance in the sensitvity range of the double cone.

#computing achromatic contrast

blue.tit.xyz$DL<-(log(blue.tit.xyz$DC)-log(0.001))/0.05



boxplot(DL~obs, data=blue.tit.xyz, ylab="brightness (JND)")

2.9 Functions tri and di

These functions compute chromatic coordinates for tri- (xy) and di-chromatic (x) visual systems. As with tetra you have to run the corresponding scripts from Appendix 1 before you can run the functions below.

To show how they work we will compute chromatic coordinates for the four blue tit colour patches analysed above using snake visual sensitivities (from Thamnophis sirtalis, Sillman et al. 1997 J. Comp Physiol A 181: 89-101) assuming a Weber fraction of 0.02 for the L cone and cone proportions: 0.137:0.22:1 (S:M:L; as done in Stuart-Fox et al. 2008 Biol. Lett.). Note that this analysis is for demonstrative purposes alone, since as far as we are aware there is no data on the noise-to-signal ratio of snake photoreceptors and we are assuming that the optical medium has similar properties to birds.

require(pavo)

snake.sense <- sensmodel(c(358.4,481.2,554),beta=TRUE, oiltype = c("T", "C","R"),om= TRUE)



plot(snake.sense, ylab="sensitivity")

To facilitate plotting PCxyz lines we can compute xyz coordinates for PC1, PC2 and PC3 lines.

PCload<- as.data.frame(unclass(loadings(PCs)))#computing xyz coordinates for PC1



#backcalculates XYZ values based on PC1.

anas$xPC1 <- with(anas, PC1*PCload[1,1]+mean(anas$x))

anas$yPC1 <- with(anas, PC1* PCload [2,1]+mean(anas$y))

anas$zPC1 <- with(anas, PC1* PCload [3,1]+mean(anas$z))



#we can do the same for PC2

#backcalculates xyz values for PC2

anas$xPC2 <- with(anas, PC2*PCload[1,2]+mean(anas$x))

anas$yPC2 <- with(anas, PC2* PCload [2,2]+mean(anas$y))

anas$zPC2 <- with(anas, PC2* PCload [3,2]+mean(anas$z))



#and PC3

#backcalculates xyz values for PC3

anas$xPC3 <- with(anas, PC3*PCload[1,3]+mean(anas$x))

anas$yPC3 <- with(anas, PC3* PCload [2,3]+mean(anas$y))

anas$zPC3 <- with(anas, PC3* PCload [3,3]+mean(anas$z))

3.4 Relating chromatic variation to spectral shape

Next, we relate variation in spectral shape to PC1 and PC2. We start by computing and plotting average spectra for the four quartiles of PC1 and PC2 (note this can also be done for PC3 if deemed necessary).

First PC1:

#assigns the dataset to be used [to keep the code generic]

Data<-anas



#assigns interquantile ranges based on PC1 and PC2

anas$PC1q <-factor(1+(Data$PC1>quantile(Data$PC1, probs=0.25) & Data$PC1<=quantile(Data$PC1, probs=0.5))+2*(Data$PC1>quantile(Data$PC1, probs=0.5) & Data$PC1<=quantile(Data$PC1, probs=0.75))+3*(Data$PC1>quantile(Data$PC1, probs=0.75) & Data$PC1<=max(Data$PC1)))

anas$PC2q <-factor(1+(Data$PC2>quantile(Data$PC2, probs=0.25) & Data$PC2<=quantile(Data$PC2, probs=0.5))+2*(Data$PC2>quantile(Data$PC2, probs=0.5) & Data$PC2<=quantile(Data$PC2, probs=0.75))+3*(Data$PC2>quantile(Data$PC2, probs=0.75) & Data$PC2<=max(Data$PC2)))



#average spectra of the 4 interquantile ranges belonging to PC1 [note that we only select columns corresponding to reflectance spectra]

spectra<-(aggregate(anas[,14:94], by=list(q=anas$PC1q), mean)[,-1])



#transposing

spectra<-na.omit(as.data.frame(t(spectra)))



#creating a wavelength vector

wavelength<-seq(300,700,along=spectra$V1)



# setting a colour palette

col.pal<-terrain.colors(n=5)



#finds the max reflectance to adjust ylim automatically 

ymax<-max(I(spectra$V1/mean(spectra$V1)), I(spectra$V2/mean(spectra$V2)), I(spectra$V3/mean(spectra$V3)), I(spectra$V4/mean(spectra$V4)))



#plots average spectra for each quartile

plot(I(spectra$V1/mean(spectra$V1))~wavelength, ylim=c(0, ymax), xlab="wavelength", ylab="normalised reflectance", pch=0, col="white")  

par(fig=c(0,1,0,1), new=TRUE)

lines(loess(I(spectra$V1/mean(spectra$V1))~wavelength, span=0.99), ylim=c(0, ymax), xlab="wavelength", ylab="normalised reflectance", lwd=4, col=col.pal[4])  

par(fig=c(0,1,0,1), new=TRUE)

lines(loess(I(spectra$V2/mean(spectra$V2))~wavelength, span=0.99), ylim=c(0, ymax), ylab="normalised reflectance", lwd=4, col=col.pal[3])

par(fig=c(0,1,0,1), new=TRUE)

lines(loess(I(spectra$V3/mean(spectra$V3))~wavelength, span=0.99), ylim=c(0, ymax), ylab="reflectance", lwd=4, col=col.pal[2])

par(fig=c(0,1,0,1), new=TRUE)

sd<-PCs$sdev

range<-c(max(PCs$scores[,1])-min(PCs$scores[,1]),max(PCs$scores[,2])-min(PCs$scores[,2]),max(PCs$scores[,3])-min(PCs$scores[,3]))

pc<-c("PC1", "PC2", "PC3")

bt.pre$yPC1 <- with(bt.pre, PC1* PCload [2,1]+mean(bt.pre$y))



bt.pre$zPC1 <- with(bt.pre, PC1* PCload [3,1]+mean(bt.pre$z))

5.4 Relating chromatic variation to spectral shape

#assigns the dataset to be used

Data<-bt.pre

#computes quantiles on PC1 and PC2

Data$PC1q <-factor(1+(Data$PC1>quantile(Data$PC1, probs=0.25) & Data$PC1<=quantile(Data$PC1, probs=0.5))+2*(Data$PC1>quantile(Data$PC1, probs=0.5) & Data$PC1<=quantile(Data$PC1, probs=0.75))+3*(Data$PC1>quantile(Data$PC1, probs=0.75) & Data$PC1<=max(Data$PC1)))

Data$PC2q <-factor(1+(Data$PC2>quantile(Data$PC2, probs=0.25) & Data$PC2<=quantile(Data$PC2, probs=0.5))+2*(Data$PC2>quantile(Data$PC2, probs=0.5) & Data$PC2<=quantile(Data$PC2, probs=0.75))+3*(Data$PC2>quantile(Data$PC2, probs=0.75) & Data$PC2<=max(Data$PC2)))

5.7 Comparing centroids

Finally, we can compare the centroids between groups. A multivariate comparison of means is usually done with the Hotelling test (T^2 ) (Johnson and Wichern 2007). This test, however, assumes multivariate normality of all groups and, crucially, similar covariance matrices between groups.These assumptions can be somewhat relaxed for large samples but do apply to the modest sample sizes in our case (Johnson and Wichern 2007).

Multivariate normality There are various tests for multivariate normality. Simulation studies (Farrell et al. 2007) suggest that three test perform well to detect departures from normality: Roystons test (which is the equivalent to the univariate Shapiro-Wilk test), Henze-Zirklers test (which measures the distance between two distribution functions) and Mardias test (which tests for multivariate skewness and kurtosis). All these can be carried out with the package MVN (Korkmaz and Goksuluk 2014). Visual assessment of normality is also important and Q-Q plots are also provided in MVN.

Equality of covariance matrices Equality of covariance matrices can be tested with Boxs M test although this test is believed to be very sensitive to small differences in covariance structure. This test can be implemented with the function cov.Mtest written by Michail Tsagris and found in Appendix 1.

This test requires the data (xyz coordinates) and a numeric vector identifying the groups. We bind pre-manipulation with UV(+) and UV(-) xyz coordiantes respectively and create a vector indicating group (1=pre-manipulation, 2=UV(+) or UV(-)).

Comparing pre-manipulation with UV(+) covariance matrices

treat.pre.plus<-c(rep(1, length(bt.pre[,1])), rep(2, length(bt.plus[,1])))

The results suggest that the covariance matrices differ, in particular UV(-) from pre-manipulation and UV(+). However, Boxs M test is notorious for its sensitivity. Thus, it has been recommended that if sample sizes are equal the results from the test should be disregarded (Tabachnick and Fidell 2007) because these multivariate tests are robust. However, if sample sizes are unequal and Boxs M test shows p<0.001 one has to compare the variances and covariances between groups. If the groups with the largest sample sizes show higher variances and covariances then the test is robust, if it is the other way around the difference in covariance matrices can be problematic and alternatives are needed.

Given that we do have unequal sample sizes between groups and that comparing the UV(-) covariance matrices with UV(+) and pre-manipulation yields p-values for Boxs M test below 0.001 we should have a look at the covariance matrices.

The covariance matrices show that variances for x and z are higher for the UV(-) treatment compared to pre-manipulation. Some of these differences can be visualised in a scatterplot matrix.

#Scatterplot matrix

require(car)

Summarizing, our data shows multivariate normality but UV(-) has a different covariance matrix than pre-manipulation or UV(+). This may preclude the use of Hotellings test. There are two alternatives (Johnson and Wichern 2007) which can be computed using the function meanTest from Appendix 1. The first alternative (test=chisq, pp.291-293 in Johnson and Wichern (2007)), which applies to large sample sizes, does not assume multivariate normality nor equality of variances; while the second one (test=approx, pp.294-296 in Johnson and Wichern (2007)), which can be used with smaller sample sizes (as are ours here), requires multivariate normality but not equality of covariance matrices. The latter is equivalent to the Welch solution of comparing univariate means between two populations with different variances.

Here for the sake of this tutorial we run all three alternatives of the test (hotelling, chisq and approx), although the latter is the one that is probably better suited to our data. Note that in addition to the test statistics the function returns the multivariate differences in xyz and their associated 95% CIs.
